textMap.PRIMARY: What Kind of American Are You

In "The Man in the High Castle" the Japanese Attacked Pearl Harbor in April, 1941, (rather than December, 1941). President Bricker's isolationist outlook and refusal to adequately prepare for a potential war emboldened the Japanese Empire.

For the set build of the Nazi laboratory in the Poconos, the production design team made the consoles fully operational and controllable. All the buttons and switches worked, and the images on the monitors were tailored to the proposed purpose of each bay.
Much of the mineshaft laboratory sequence was filmed on US Thanksgiving, though the filming took place in Canada.
The scenes that show Juliana, Wyatt and their comrades spying on the Nazis through the vent in the Poconos laboratory were filmed on a secondary set that was separate from the main laboratory.
In history, the Nazis impounded thousands of works of art across Europe, burned books and destroyed many famous landmarks, though none were as large and iconic as the Statue of Liberty.

Abendsen reveals an integral rule of travel to John Smith, which is that an individual can only pass into another world where their twin has died or never existed at all. This concept is rooted in the Pauli Exclusion Principle in quantum mechanical theory.
Another law of travel in "The Man in the High Castle" is that travelers are able to move into worlds where they are longed for and where people exist that are objects of their longing.
